# CleanMateX Flutter UI/UX Rules

## UX Principles
CleanMateX mobile apps are operational products, not design experiments.

Optimize for:
- speed
- clarity
- low tap count
- low cognitive load
- touch friendliness
- consistency
- dense but readable workflow screens

## Localization
- All user-facing strings must come from localization.
- No hardcoded UI strings.
- Every new key must include both English and Arabic.
- UI must support RTL correctly.
- Do not assume short English-length labels.
- Avoid unsafe string concatenation for translated content.
- Dates, time, numbers, and currencies must be localized properly.

## Layout Rules
- Use consistent spacing.
- Respect safe areas.
- Keep primary actions obvious.
- Support smaller phones and larger phones cleanly.
- Avoid overflow-prone fixed-width assumptions.
- Extract repeated layout patterns into shared widgets.

## Reusable Widgets
Prefer shared widgets for:
- buttons
- text fields
- dropdowns
- chips
- cards
- empty states
- error states
- loading placeholders
- confirmation dialogs
- bottom sheets

Before creating a new widget:
1. check existing core widgets
2. extend or compose if possible
3. only create new if needed

## Screen States
Every non-trivial screen should account for:
- initial
- loading
- success
- empty
- error
- offline if applicable

Do not leave blank screens or raw exception text.

## Forms
- Validate client-side for obvious input issues.
- Preserve typed input on validation failure.
- Prevent duplicate submits while in progress.
- Show field-level validation when useful.
- For long forms, split into sections or steps.

## Operational UI
For staff/driver-style workflows:
- prioritize one-hand use when possible
- minimize typing
- make scan/photo/location actions fast
- keep destructive actions clearly separated
- reduce modal overload
- show status and next action clearly

## Accessibility
- Reasonable contrast
- readable touch targets
- semantic labels where practical
- avoid relying on color alone to convey status

## Visual Consistency
- Use shared theme tokens and app-wide color/text styles.
- Avoid ad-hoc colors, font sizes, paddings, and radii.
- Keep cards, buttons, text fields, and chips visually consistent across screens.
- Use a single style language for customer and driver apps unless a feature explicitly needs a distinct treatment.

## UX Anti-Patterns
Reject:
- visually noisy screens
- overuse of dialogs
- too many nested accordions
- action buttons with unclear meaning
- icon-only destructive actions without labels or confirmation
- hidden important actions behind obscure gestures